{
  "text": "The cytokine profiles observed with MV1-F4 vaccinees were remarkably similar between responding animals. For CD4+ T cells, we observed a TNFa and IL-2 bias that contrasted with CD8+ T cell responses with a TNFa and IFNc bias. Such responses are indicative of a T helper 1 (Th1) cell response characterized by the production of IFN-c, IL-2 and TNF-a [CITATION_1] . However, IL-4 responses were not assessed here so a Th1/Th2 mixed pattern of cytokine release cannot be excluded. The bias of CD4+ T cell cytokine responses to TNFa and IL-2 suggests a central memory response rather than terminally differentiated CD4 effector cell response, which was characterised by higher levels of IFN-c and TNF-a expression [CITATION_2] . CD8+ memory T cells can quickly produce a variety of cytokines including IFNc, TNFa and to a lesser extent IL-2 [CITATION_3] , matching the profile we observed against F4 peptides. The low frequency of multifunctional T cells, positive for all three cytokines, is likely due to the necessary use of peripheral blood lymphocytes deficient in effector memory T cells when compared with mucosal sites [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "4319699",
